title: For Sale:  Nightvision Robot? THROWBOT XT
postcontent:
The Throwbot® XT is, pound-for-pound, the most versatile, robust, stealthy and easy-to-deploy tactical robot system in the world.

Inherently water and dust resistant, the Throwbot XT is a personal sensor system for tactical operators. It weighs just 1.2lbs (540g) and can be thrown up to 120 feet (36m). The sensor is also exceptionally quiet (operating at just 22 decibels) and is equipped with an infrared optical system that activates automatically when the ambient light is low, enabling the operator to see in complete darkness.

Once deployed, the micro-robot can be directed by the operator to quietly move through a structure and transmit video and audio to the handheld Operator Control Unit II (OCU II). These stealth capabilities can be utilized to locate armed subjects, confirm the presence of hostages or innocent civilians, listen in on conversations, and reveal the layout of rooms – information that can save lives and increase the success of high-risk operations. 

The robot may be purchased with or without audio (listening) capabilities, or upgraded to listening-enabled at a later date. The Throwbot XT may also be specified in any of three predetermined transmitting frequencies, enabling operators to use up to three robots in the same environment at the same time.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Saiga AK-47, 7.62x39, Fully Converted
postcontent:
This rifle started out as a standard Saiga Sporter and was quickly restored to it’s full AK glory.  All conversion holes were welded closed, and all of the metal was blasted, parkerized, and duracoated.

It features a genuine PK-23 red dot optic on a Tim Heffron Special Edition low mount.  It wears plum colored furniture from K-var.  Trigger is a Tapco G2 unit for legality and reliability.  Accepts all Mil-Spec magazines.

All of the donor parts such as the dust cover, rear sight, gas block, flash hider, gas tube, safety selector, cleaning rod, and trigger guard came from a numbers matching AK74 kit.  Muzzle brake was properly machined to upsize for the 7.62 projectile.

Barrel was shortened approximately 3 inches and finished off with an 11 degree target crown.  Muzzle brake has been permanently affixed per ATF regulations to maintain legal barrel length of 16 inches.

Includes 3 thirty round mags and a 75 round Romanian turn-key drum.

Looks great and shoots perfectly.  You will not be disappointed with this piece.

postcontent:
Kimber Solo Carry STS - I love how this gun looks (better than the pictures!) and I love how it shoots - super accurate - easy to place your shots!  The recoil does not bother me at all - no damage to my hand or fingers.  Super smooth and comfortable in the hand - small and a dream to carry anywhere!!  

Purchased new in June of 2012 by an acquaintance and I bought it from him after he had shot 100 rounds through it - he bought two - different styles.  These guns are still hard to find and I’ve done a gentle, thorough test of this gun so you’ll pretty much know what ammo you can shoot with it.  No Plus P ammo was used in this gun and no reloads, though it is rated for Plus P for self defense.  It’s just not recommended that that be used much otherwise.   And though it may shoot reloads just fine, I have not tried any.   I only used standardized factory loads - so I could accurately predict what it would shoot the best.

It’s had a total of around 250 rounds through it.   

Included with this fine gun is the original magazine.   Also included is the Original Box with matching Serial Numbers, the soft zippered pouch and all of the original papers, the lock, etc.

Yours for $735 Cash

Also, buy this now, and you can get more magazines before I up them to Ebay.   
$30 for another regular magazine or 
$35 for an extended magazine.   
I also have extra wood grips that might be an option.
I did not believe I’d ever sell this gun.


Of this gun, Kimber says,    "USE ONLY RECOMMENDED AMMUNITION
Solo is designed to function optimally using premium hollow-point self-defense factory ammunition with bullet weights of 124 or 147 grains.

EXAMPLES INCLUDE:

• Federal® Hydra-Shok® JHP
• Remington® Golden Saber™ HPJ
• Hornady TAP® JHP

While other ammunition may perform well, lighter bullets and inconsistent pressures that can be found in lower-quality ammunition may lead to decreased slide cycle time and compromise function." 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Now, since I’ve not been ready to go to the self-defense ammo yet, but have still been shooting practice ammo with my guns, I set out to see which ammo,of the ammo available to me, this gun shot the best.   I assumed that most 124 grain and 147 grain would shoot the best.

I’ve shot the following rounds with NO PROBLEMS whatsoever:

1.  Federal 147gr JHP 9ms 10 rounds
2.  American Eagle 147gr FMJ 10 rounds
3.  PMC Bronze 124GR FMJ 9mm 50 rounds
4.  Remington 124 Gr Metal Case R9MM2 25 rounds
5.  Remington 115 Gr JHP R9mm1 (20 year old ammo) 30 rounds
6.  Remington-Peters JHP (Older Ammo) - 17 rounds -no problem
7.  Hirtenberger 100gr Soft Pt Fl (lead fill) Law Enforcement Grade J =P+   5 rounds

I later shot some more of these with the gun dirty and again had no problems with them.

I  also shot:

1.  Blazer 124 Grain FMJ Aluminum (type 3578)  Shot 10 Rounds - later 20 rounds -no problem
2.  American Eagle 115 Grain - Shot 15 rounds - no problem
3.  Remington UMC 115 Grain FMG - I shot 14 rounds - no problem

However, later with the gun dirtier - I did have a problem or two with these three ammos.


With the following I had serious continued problems - I would not put these in the Solo again for any reason:

1.  Remington 147 Grain UMC 23732 L9MM9   The gun was dirty - but the 15th shell stuck in the barrel, and then 3 shots later stuck again Like the shell expanded too much.   Not a feeding problem but an ejection one.
2.  Aguila FMJ 124Gr - 9 rounds - last one a double feed.  Note, this is actually a FTE quickly enough.  When one shell fails to eject in time and the next shell tries to load - both are sitting there together - called a double feed.    Shot more later - even more problems with gun dirty.
3.  Blazer Bronze 124 Gr   Terrible - tried many times - Round would not eject right -So second round would be blocked by it.  Gun dirty, but still not an OK round for this.
4.  Speer Lawman 115Gr FMJ 53615 - Nothing but problems - every second shot.   Gun dirty, but still not an OK round for this.

So, in summary - In addition to what Kimber recommends for self defense, this gun fires great with most 147 Grain ammo, and the better 124 grain ammo I’ve tested.  Clearly, because of its short stroke slide (the gun is only 5 ½ inches long) it needs more powerful ammo to push its powerful spring all the way back quickly so the next round can load.)   Like a lot of people, I was curious enough to try all of my ammo (no reloads though) to see how well it operated.   The gun shoots great, is the most accurate of the small 9mm for me, and is a pleasure to shoot.  I cannot fault the gun for not liking underpowered and lower quality ammo.   It is actually my favorite CC sized gun to shoot, but is just too easy for me to shoot (see more of this at end of article)

I have also owned the Kahr MK9, the Ruger LC9, the Sig P938, the Colt Mustang (380), and have also shot the Kahr CM9, CW45, the Beretta Nano, the Micro Eagle (380), and a Bersa 380.

In addition to the thumb safety and an inertia firing pin, “The Kimber system also utilizes a firing pin safety that prevents the gun from being fired unless the trigger is fully depressed.”

Wondering why I'm selling? Only one reason - and that's with great regret! This gun shoots too easy (as did my MK9 and as do all of the striker fired guns). The trigger is smooth as butter. And it has adequate pull before it fires.  It's right on track for a great striker fired gun.  But, as I'm finding out - I'm a safety nut and am selling all guns that do not have redundant safeties. This does have a thumb safety and an inertia firing pin.   But it’s still a little too easy for ME to shoot.

I want to carry a 1911 style gun with the chamber loaded and the hammer down, and have only single action to where it can only be fired by cocking my hammer first - and that only when I need it.  So this is leading me to the Colt Mustang or Sig P238 or Sig P938.   These have all of the above.   But some will say - “Well, what if you are cocking those in your pocket and the hammer slips?”     No big deal - I can cock it again.   If your hammer slips while you’re cocking it on these guns - (with you finger off of the trigger now), it falls into a half-cock safety position - it does not hit the firing pin.   Just about fool-proof.	

(On a non 1911 style gun, then, I’d want a Thumb safety, a Magazine safety or de-cocker and long hard action pulls - like the Ruger LC9, old S&W Gen 3 guns, and the Bersa 380's.)    

And, yes, I'm more afraid of me - not the gun. Most new guns are drop safety safe and will not accidentally fire. I've just become afraid of all striker fired guns at this point - because I like to shoot them a little bit too much and find my finger on that active trigger too soon. 

None of these other guns are as nice to hold as the Solo - the P938 actually feels a little bit
strange and unbalanced, and it’s not as accurate for me,  and it’s rougher to shoot.  After 50 rounds its safety wore through the skin on my thumb’s lower joint and the trigger’s serrations are way too rough (though I filed them down).  But still, I'd rather get shot than be too quick on the shoot. But, on the other hand, in a crisis, I'm cool enough that the extra split second to pull the hammer is not something I'm worried about.

You are looking at a deep concealment holster/garment similar to Smart Carry (TM) and Thunderwear (TM). But why pay $20-30 MORE for their product if you don't even know it will work for you? This holster can be used ambidextrously and can accomodate an addtional magazine. Additionally, it incorporates an extra pocket where you can keep your ID, passport or cash. Rough Rider ... the very image conjured up is of the rugged men led by Theodore Roosevelt up Kettle Hill and San Juan Hill over 100 years ago during our war with Spain. That same image of ruggedness might also be applied to the newest Big Bore Rough Rider revolver from Heritage. Almost the "spitting image" of the Single Action Army still be carried by some troops during the Spanish-American War, this latest six-shooter comes chambered for the legendary .45 Colt cartridge, .44-40 and .357 Magnum. This fine handgun can be had in the traditional 4.75", 5.5" and 7.5" barrel lengths, just like the original. Blue, nickel, stainless and blue/color-case hardened finishes are available and each gun is fitted with attractive one-piece cocobolo grips. The action features a frame mounted inertia firing pin and transfer bar for added protection. Old World gun maker Pietta of Italy start certain parts for us. They are a family run operation, just like Heritage Manufacturing. Then those certain parts are finished by Heritage, then plated then fully assembled by us in the good old US.

Perfect for the exciting sport of western action shooting, the Big Bore Rough Rider embodies the flavor of the Old West and will also serve anyone who wants an accurate and reliable sidearm for other outdoor activities.
